<div id="outline-container-org0da2255" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="org0da2255">Open Source Software Development</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-org0da2255">
<p>
We  briefly discussed Open Source Software in the <a href="linux101.html">linux 101</a> lecture.
Lets dig a little deeper. 
</p>

<p>
When we use the term Open Source Software, we are referring to the copyrights and
licenses surrounding <b>intellectual property.</b>
</p>

<p>
Intellectual property is considered an intangibel asset.
</p>

<p>
The laws regarding ownership of Intellectul Property fall under 3 broad areas
</p>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orgdf9bb3e" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgdf9bb3e">patents</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-orgdf9bb3e">
<p>
inventions
</p>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org46fd1b6" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org46fd1b6">trademarks</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org46fd1b6">
<p>
Recognizable <b>Sign</b> or <b>Logo</b> that distinguishes an enterprise
</p>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orgef094ef" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgef094ef">copyrights</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-orgef094ef">
<p>
A copyright is used to describe a person's <b>ownership rights to an *original expression of
creativity.</b>
</p>

<p>
The ownership of Source code falls under the purview of Copyright law.
</p>

<p>
So as programmers our original expressiom of creativity is source code.
So We can choose to license the rights to it however we wish.
</p>

<p>
If we decide to use an open source license we are allowing anyone
to use, study, change and distribute it in anyway that is specified by
the particuliar open source license we use.
</p>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org65caf52" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org65caf52">Benefits of the Open source license</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org65caf52">
<p>
When source code is available for inspection, modification and
enhancement it stimulates public collaboration. Allowing
the developer community to have open access to the source code
can lead to better.
</p>

<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Security</li>
<li>Affordability</li>
<li>Transparency</li>
<li>Interoperability</li>
<li>Scalabiility</li>
<li>localization</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orgf1b438f" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgf1b438f">Open Source Defintion</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-orgf1b438f">
<p>
An organization called the Open Source Initiative has published a
document with their definition of what constitutes an open source
license.  They offer a cerification for licenses that meet their
standard of open source.
</p>

<p>
Here is some of OSI OSD
</p>

<ol class="org-ol">
<li>Free Redistribution
Any party can sell of give away the software as a component
of an aggregated software distribution</li>

<li>Acces to the human readable Source Code</li>

<li>Must allow modifications and derived works that can be distributed
under the same license as the original</li>

<li>No discrimination against persons or groups.</li>

<li>No discrimination against fields of endeavor.</li>

<li>License must Be tech neutral. Meaning the license doesn't restrict
the software to any particuliar hardware or platform.</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>


<div id="outline-container-org57b7eb3" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org57b7eb3">links to projects and their licenses</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org57b7eb3">
